mmitments of a group of Baptist women whose experiences have been informed by the realities of life in a rural, southern community. In these lives, "spirituality" emerges as a space for creative agency, of vital importance to the ways in which these women interpret, inform, and reshape their social conditions--conditions often characterized by limited access to job opportunities, health care, and equitable schooling. In the words of these women, and in Marla F. Frederick's deft analysis, we see how spirituality—expressed as gratitude, empathy, or righteous discontent—operates as a transformative power in women's interactions with others, and in their own more intimate renegotiations of self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American womenxReligious life. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aafrican americans.  aamerican south.  aamerican women.  abaptist women.  ablack americans.  ablack experience.  ablack religion.  ablack women.  achristianity.  acultural analysis.  acultural politics.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  afaith and religion.  afemale relationships.  agender studies.  anonfiction.  apersonal interviews.  aregional history.  arural south.  asocial conditions.  asouthern baptists.  aspiritual community.  aspiritual lives.  aspirituality.  asystemic oppression.  awomen of faith.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023392840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093645440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936454/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles